Why does this matter ? 

Because if it was a retaliatory attack, arguably Israel can forgo a serious response. 

But if this was something entirely different — designed to disturb commerce/normalizations, then with no serious response from Israel, Iran will escalate further.
As I wrote yesterday, Iran’s attack on the Israeli cargo ship was likely not retaliatory at all. Rather is likely designed to complicate Israeli-Arab commerce/normalization.

That assessment, even if well intentioned, is likely garbage. To avenge #natanz and or #fakhrizadeh Iran won’t merely target a civilian cargo ship — nor would they do it in a way that would only cause minimal damage — which is what they did here.

Perhaps for that reason we’ve seen reports yesterday out of Israel suggesting that Iran’s attack on the Israeli cargo ship was a retaliation for #natanz, &/or #fakhrizadeh, (or Syria) — and that it would make sense to just let this round come to an end without further escalation.

As a general matter, Israel doesn’t have the freehand it did with Trump in the White House. That’s indisputable. 

While they’re in the initial states of formulating a common understanding on Iran, the Israelis are certainly trying not to rock the boat.
